Body:
PROS:- light-weight- easy to push and steer- easy to buckle and unbuckle- unfolds easily (with one strong shake out, I don't close the latch so I can unfold the stroller with one hand, so far the stroller stays collapsed even without the latch)- folds easily (once you get the hang of it — using both hands, I push the red buttons, then grab the tray and pull that up toward me)- affordable (just under 70 dollars when I purchased it)- canopy big enough to provide good coverage from sun and light rain- has tray and basket- seat can be reclined for sleeping childCONS:- not a true 1-hand-fold- wish seat could be adjusted to be more upright, most straight setting is a bit too reclined for our child, so he slouches in the seat- one wheel was almost impossible to attach, needed to use a lot of force to push locking pin through at a very awkward angle- basket open in the front, so items may slide outWe needed a stroller for our 1-year-old that is a step up from those cheap umbrella strollers, but not as fancy as a full stroller with all the bells and whistles. This one caught my eye because of the features listed above and the promised 1-hand-fold — I use this stroller every day for daycare drop-offs with a toddler and a baby, so I loved the idea of being able to fold up the stroller with the baby on my hip. Unfortunately, you really do need two hands to properly fold the stroller together and technically you are supposed to lock it with a little latch too (though I've found that it stays pretty well together once collapsed). I was about to return the stroller, because it didn't fold easily with one hand, but after researching more I arrived at my original conclusion that for the price, this stroller is still the best option. I tried it for a few more days and once I figure out how to quickly collapse it, I just accepted that I still need both hands to fold it and I decided I still liked the other features enough to keep it.After having used the stroller for a few months for daycare drop-offs and outings, it has grown on me and I do like it. The two things that I still wish were improved are:1) the seat should adjust to be more upright, so my baby doesn't slouch as much in the seat; maybe the seat area could also be a bit bigger to give more traction for the baby to hold himself more upright2) the basket front should be closed so that things don't slide outThe other stroller we considered is the Summer Infant 2015 3D Lite Convenience Stroller (

 Summer Infant 2015 3D Lite Convenience Stroller, Black
















  ), but it doesn't have the tray and the basket seemed too small to hold our lunch boxes and daycare stuff.
